Nadav Rotem

·
Nov 27, 2021
memcpy and memset are sensitive to different things at different buffer sizes. When the buffers are small, branch prediction and code layout are very important. When the buffers are large ILP (saturating load/store ports) matters.
1
4
58
Nadav Rotem
@nadavrot
·
Nov 27, 2021
There are different impls for different buffer sizes. For sizes 1-4, you use IFs and byte-wide stores. For larger sizes you use wide scalars and later vector registers. It's important to make the decision tree match the size distribution to do well on the common case.
1

One of the cool tricks that people use is what I call "telescopic ld/st". I don't know of another name. You copy any number of 32 .. 64 bytes using two ymm vectors, by aligning one to the start of the buffer, and the other one to the end. There will be overlap, but this is ok:
